<div class="feature-header-text">

<a
    href="https://foreignpolicy.com/category/q-a/"
    class="department-name">
    <h3 class="department">Q&amp;A</h3></a>
<span
    class="hed-heading"
    href="https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/04/16/this-restoration-will-take-at-least-a-decade/">
    <h1 class="hed">‘This Restoration Will Take at Least a Decade’</h1>
</span>
<h2 class="dek-heading">Despite being spared the worst, Notre Dame is not out of danger, says the building expert Caroline Bruzelius.</h2>
<div class="meta-data ">
    <address class="author-list">
    <span class="pre">By</span>
    <a
        href="https://foreignpolicy.com/author/michael-hirsh/"
        rel="author"
        class="author">
    Michael Hirsh</a></address>
    <span class="separator">|</span>
    <time
    pubdate
    datetime="2019-04-16"
    title="April 16th, 2019"
    class="date-time">
April 16, 2019, 1:37 PM</time>
</div>

</div>


			
						
			<div class="post-content-main initial-drop-cap shares-position">
								<p><span style="font-weight:400;">Caroline Bruzelius, an architectural historian at Duke University, has scaled the heights of Notre Dame in ways that few people have—</span><span style="font-weight:400;">and she is thus all too aware of how fragile the cathedral remains in spite of being saved from total devastation during Monday night’s raging fire. Bruzelius, an expert in Gothic cathedrals, studied the revered structure closely from top to bottom nearly four decades ago when scaffolding was erected around it for cleaning, and she later wrote a <a href="https://www.academia.edu/1983975/The_Construction_of_Notre-Dame_in_Paris">scholarly article</a> going into great detail about the building’s strengths and weaknesses. She spoke with <span class="fp-red" style="color:#eb1414;">Foreign Policy</span> on Tuesday about the long road of reconstruction that lies ahead.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight:400;"><strong><span class="fp-red" style="color:#eb1414;">Foreign Policy:</span></strong> The news looks better today than the worst that was feared last night regarding damage from the fire.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight:400;"><strong>Caroline Bruzelius:</strong> I think it’s going to take quite a while to really understand the extent of the damage and to which parts. There is the stained glass, the altar, the structures, and the building, so all of this will require different kinds of experts analyzing their different areas of specialty. I’m particularly concerned with the condition of the stone walls. That fire was immense and incredibly hot—although stone won’t actually burn, it can be terribly damaged by great heat. The whole area of the vaults and upper walls will need to be assessed.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight:400;">I am imagining, though I don’t know, that this restoration will take at least a decade. The critical thing will be to cover the building, to find a way to protect what are now the exposed upper surfaces of the vaults—from water, from the weather—and also the building downstairs.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_964968" class="wp-caption alignnone none text_width"><a href="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137466161.jpg">            <span
                style="padding-bottom:66.625%;
        "
                class="image-attachment -ratioscale">
        <img
            data-srcset="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137466161.jpg 4917w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137466161.jpg?resize=150,100 150w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137466161.jpg?resize=550,367 550w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137466161.jpg?resize=768,512 768w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137466161.jpg?resize=1536,1024 1536w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137466161.jpg?resize=2048,1365 2048w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137466161.jpg?resize=400,267 400w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137466161.jpg?resize=401,267 401w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137466161.jpg?resize=800,533 800w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137466161.jpg?resize=1920,1280 1920w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137466161.jpg?resize=275,183 275w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137466161.jpg?resize=325,217 325w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137466161.jpg?resize=600,400 600w"
            data-src="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137466161.jpg?w=800"
            alt=""
            class="image alignnone size-text_width wp-image-964968 -fit -lazy">
        <noscript>
            <img
                src="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137466161.jpg?w=800"
                alt=""
                class="image alignnone size-text_width wp-image-964968 -fit">
        </noscript>
        </span>
        </a><p id="caption-attachment-964968" class="wp-caption-text">Flames glow through the windows of Notre Dame Cathedral in Paris on April 15. (Michel Stoupak/NurPhoto via Getty Images) <!-- caption placeholder --></p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight:400;"><strong><span class="fp-red" style="color:#eb1414;">FP:</span></strong> Based on your research on the construction of Notre Dame and the history of it, how vulnerable was it just before the fire? They were doing reconstruction for a reason, after all.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight:400;"><strong>CB:</strong> Well, yes, it was badly in need of restoration in the parts we do not see when we walk in the building, and I’m talking specifically about the enormous wooden structure between the upper parts of the vaults and the roof. That’s old timber. For centuries, it gets heated in the summer and frozen in the winter, and that was incredibly flammable, and that’s why the fire was so horrific and spectacular. It was those old timbers that were burning so ferociously. We saw the fire spread from one section to another in rapid succession.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight:400;"><strong><span class="fp-red" style="color:#eb1414;">FP:</span></strong> Do you think it was something of a miracle that so much was preserved?</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight:400;"><strong>CB:</strong> Yeah, when I saw the photographs late last night of the interior, I was hugely relieved because it looked as though only a couple of the vaults were penetrated by either the spire falling or by beams falling through them. Now we don’t know about the condition of the rest of the vaults. As soon as the fire is over, the weakening of the structure may mean that things will be falling down from high up. Remember that a Gothic cathedral is a dynamic structure, where you have vaults pushing out and flying buttresses pushing inward, and when that system is compromised, it may become very dangerous.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_964965" class="wp-caption alignnone none text_width"><a href="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137435929.jpg">            <span
                style="padding-bottom:68.125%;
        "
                class="image-attachment -ratioscale">
        <img
            data-srcset="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137435929.jpg 1500w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137435929.jpg?resize=150,102 150w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137435929.jpg?resize=550,374 550w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137435929.jpg?resize=768,523 768w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137435929.jpg?resize=400,272 400w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137435929.jpg?resize=401,273 401w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137435929.jpg?resize=800,545 800w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137435929.jpg?resize=275,187 275w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137435929.jpg?resize=325,221 325w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137435929.jpg?resize=600,408 600w"
            data-src="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137435929.jpg?w=800"
            alt=""
            class="image alignnone size-text_width wp-image-964965 -fit -lazy">
        <noscript>
            <img
                src="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137435929.jpg?w=800"
                alt=""
                class="image alignnone size-text_width wp-image-964965 -fit">
        </noscript>
        </span>
        </a><p id="caption-attachment-964965" class="wp-caption-text">A burned-through hole in the roof from the interior of Notre Dame Cathedral on April 15. (Philippe Wojazer/AFP/Getty Images) <!-- caption placeholder --></p></div>
<div id="attachment_964966" class="wp-caption alignnone none text_width"><a href="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438174.jpg">            <span
                style="padding-bottom:66.625%;
        "
                class="image-attachment -ratioscale">
        <img
            data-srcset="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438174.jpg 1800w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438174.jpg?resize=150,100 150w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438174.jpg?resize=550,367 550w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438174.jpg?resize=768,512 768w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438174.jpg?resize=1536,1024 1536w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438174.jpg?resize=400,267 400w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438174.jpg?resize=401,267 401w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438174.jpg?resize=800,533 800w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438174.jpg?resize=275,183 275w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438174.jpg?resize=325,217 325w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438174.jpg?resize=600,400 600w"
            data-src="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438174.jpg?w=800"
            alt=""
            class="image alignnone size-text_width wp-image-964966 -fit -lazy">
        <noscript>
            <img
                src="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438174.jpg?w=800"
                alt=""
                class="image alignnone size-text_width wp-image-964966 -fit">
        </noscript>
        </span>
        </a><p id="caption-attachment-964966" class="wp-caption-text">Smoke rises in front of the altar cross at Notre Dame Cathedral on April 15. (Philippe Wojazer/AFP/Getty Images) <!-- caption placeholder --></p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight:400;"><strong><span class="fp-red" style="color:#eb1414;">FP:</span></strong> What we do seem to know at this point is that many of the relics inside and apparently the stained-glass rose windows were preserved.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight:400;"><strong>CB:</strong> That’s wonderful. Again, it depends on where the fire was concentrated. Some of the most beautiful windows in the church were in the transept arms on the north side and south side, and if those were preserved, we’re on our knees in gratitude. I haven’t yet seen pictures of them.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight:400;"><strong><span class="fp-red" style="color:#eb1414;">FP:</span></strong> Can you talk about your original interest in Notre Dame—why you researched it?</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight:400;"><strong>CB:</strong> I was actually living in Paris and working on another book, back in the late ’70s, when they began to clean the inside, and that was an amazing opportunity. There was a scaffolding erected up the entire height of the building, and when I checked around, no architectural historian trained in medieval buildings was going up and down that scaffolding. It was a lifetime opportunity to see parts of the building that normally nobody can see. I ended up writing a very long and probably deeply boring article about it because I’m interested in how buildings are put up.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_964967" class="wp-caption alignnone none text_width"><a href="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438115.jpg">            <span
                style="padding-bottom:66.625%;
        "
                class="image-attachment -ratioscale">
        <img
            data-srcset="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438115.jpg 1800w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438115.jpg?resize=150,100 150w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438115.jpg?resize=550,367 550w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438115.jpg?resize=768,512 768w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438115.jpg?resize=1536,1024 1536w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438115.jpg?resize=400,267 400w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438115.jpg?resize=401,267 401w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438115.jpg?resize=800,533 800w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438115.jpg?resize=275,183 275w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438115.jpg?resize=325,217 325w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438115.jpg?resize=600,400 600w"
            data-src="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438115.jpg?w=800"
            alt=""
            class="image alignnone size-text_width wp-image-964967 -fit -lazy">
        <noscript>
            <img
                src="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137438115.jpg?w=800"
                alt=""
                class="image alignnone size-text_width wp-image-964967 -fit">
        </noscript>
        </span>
        </a><p id="caption-attachment-964967" class="wp-caption-text">Flames and smoke billow around the gargoyles on Notre Dame Cathedral on April 15. (Thomas Samson/AFP/Getty Images) <!-- caption placeholder --></p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight:400;"><strong><span class="fp-red" style="color:#eb1414;">FP:</span></strong> And you were looking particularly at the stone walls?</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight:400;"><strong>CB:</strong> Yes, if you measure them, if you record every detail, you begin to unfold a narrative over time.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight:400;"><strong><span class="fp-red" style="color:#eb1414;">FP:</span></strong> So based on your intimate knowledge of the cathedral’s construction, can you talk about what reconstruction will entail?</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight:400;"><strong>CB:</strong> I’m guessing that will probably take a number of months just to understand how bad the damage is, where the most urgent repairs are. I imagine they’re going to have to put up wooden framework, wooden struts, in those areas especially where the vaults were partially collapsed. You don’t want more stones falling down—you need to support what has been damaged—so there’s going to be some temporary shoring up before they can really begin to repair.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_964969" class="wp-caption alignnone none section_break"><a href="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137448876.jpg">            <span
                style="padding-bottom:66.69921875%;
        "
                class="image-attachment -ratioscale">
        <img
            data-srcset="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137448876.jpg 1500w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137448876.jpg?resize=150,100 150w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137448876.jpg?resize=550,367 550w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137448876.jpg?resize=768,513 768w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137448876.jpg?resize=400,267 400w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137448876.jpg?resize=401,268 401w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137448876.jpg?resize=800,534 800w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137448876.jpg?resize=275,184 275w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137448876.jpg?resize=325,217 325w, https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137448876.jpg?resize=600,400 600w"
            data-src="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137448876.jpg"
            alt=""
            class="image alignnone size-section_break wp-image-964969 -fit -lazy">
        <noscript>
            <img
                src="https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/gettyimages-1137448876.jpg"
                alt=""
                class="image alignnone size-section_break wp-image-964969 -fit">
        </noscript>
        </span>
        </a><p id="caption-attachment-964969" class="wp-caption-text">Smoke rises over Paris from Notre Dame Cathedral on April 15. (Veronique de Viguerie/Getty Images) <!-- caption placeholder --></p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight:400;"><strong><span class="fp-red" style="color:#eb1414;">FP:</span></strong> And I guess it will be a long, long time before the public can gain access again.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight:400;"><strong>CB:</strong> Alas, that is true. But you know one thing I’m hoping is that the public will become more aware of the fragility of our historical buildings. They’ll put money in the box and ask for donations for upkeep. And maybe they’ll treat these buildings not just as the obligatory sight you go to see in Paris but really as a building that has had an enormously interesting life and has played a fundamental role in the history of France.</span></p>
<p><em>This conversation has been condensed and edited for publication.</em></p>
<div data-fp-lazy-load-image></div>								<p><span class="red-box-end"></span></p>
