ages) <!-- caption placeholder -->[\/caption]\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight:400;\"><strong><span class=\"fp-red\" style=\"color:#eb1414;\">FP:<\/span><\/strong> And I guess it will be a long, long time before the public can gain access again.<\/span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight:400;\"><strong>CB:<\/strong> Alas, that is true. But you know one thing I\u2019m hoping is that the public will become more aware of the fragility of our historical buildings. They\u2019ll put money in the box and ask for donations for upkeep. And maybe they\u2019ll treat these buildings not just as the obligatory sight you go to see in Paris but really as a building that has had an enormously interesting life and has played a fundamental role in the history of France.<\/span>\r\n\r\n<em>This conversation has been condensed and edited for publication.<\/em>","datePublished":"2019-04-16T13:37:51+00:00","dateModified":"2019-04-29T12:37:43+00:00","url":"https:\/\/foreignpolicy.com\/2019\/04\/16\/this-restoration-will-take-at-least-a-decade\/","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Michael Hirsh","url":"https:\/\/foreignpolicy.com\/author\/michael-hirsh\/"},"image":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https:\/\/foreignpolicy.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/04\/gettyimages-1137427540.jpg?w=1536","height":1024,"width":1536},"isAccessibleForFree":"False","hasPart":{"@type":"WebPageElement","isAccessibleForFree":"False","cssSelector":".post-content-main"}}</script>
